What, then, was the new ideal? It was the conception of peace by forgiveness, of conciliation instead of punishment, -in a word, the ideal of mercy. lt was indeed lor a part of this, that is, for just and humane government, that Cicero had lived and died3 and from him Julius Caesar had learnt, ere the end of his stormy career, the great political secretos forgetting offences; but the deeper ethical note, the human sympathy and tendemess oi Virgil’s appeal to the world, is all his own. In his great picture-gallery of Roman heroeS,¹ nothing surely is more strik- ing than the faint praise or open censure which he bestows on those who were merely great warriorS, like King Tullus, the Tarquins, or Torquatus “ of the cruel axe.''
